# Veil — external security frameworks

When hardening engage or platform deploy, use **Veil-native** artifacts first:

| Read | Do not |
|------|--------|
| [deploy/security/veil-controls.yaml](../../deploy/security/veil-controls.yaml) | Copy full JCSF/DAF spreadsheets into repo |
| [docs/external-security-frameworks.md](../../docs/external-security-frameworks.md) | Edit files under `.external/` |
| [docs/engage-agentic-threats.md](../../docs/engage-agentic-threats.md) | Assume every DAF practice applies to Veil |

## Workflow

1. Identify which **VEIL-* control** a change supports (add to `veil-controls.yaml` only if new).
2. Implement in **code / compose / CI** — not markdown-only.
3. Run `make test-engage-hardening` and `python3 scripts/engage/hardening-framework-audit.py`.
4. Update [engage-hardening.md](../../docs/engage-hardening.md) or [deploy-platform-hybrid.md](../../docs/deploy-platform-hybrid.md) if operator-facing.

## Skepticism checklist

- JCSF **L3–L4** may require enterprise tooling Veil does not bundle — mark as roadmap, not done.
- DAF practices about **SCM branch protection** belong in GitHub org settings + `.github/workflows`, not engage Go code.
- OWASP agentic PDFs are **landscapes**, not acceptance tests — Veil self-test stays non-destructive.
- **DAF MLSO** human-in-the-loop (T-PROD-RUN-ML-1-3) is process, not automatic in engage-api.

## Secured engage defaults

Production profile: [deploy/profiles/secure-engage.env](../../deploy/profiles/secure-engage.env) — `ENGAGE_TARGET_GUARD=block`, docker runner, deny raw command.
